<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-07-30T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-07-30T02:00:00-05:00" n="894" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d894">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">646G.9331/7–3049: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">McConaughy</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-07-30T15:00:00+08:00">July 30,
                                    1949—3 p. m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received July 30—6:35 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>2971.</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                        <p>Hinke<note n="8" xml:id="d894fn8">Frederick W. Hinke, Consul and
                                Commercial Attaché in China at Shanghai.</note> has observed
                            apparent reluctance on part British Minister (Commercial)<note n="9" xml:id="d894fn9">John Colville Hutchison.</note> to take seriously
                            need for realistic rational export controls at Hong Kong, a problem
                            which will become pressing once Communists take Canton. Until British
                            agree to some effective supervision over Hong Kong exports to Communist
                            China, western powers will obviously lack essential economic leverage
                            for dealing with Communists on important problems. Unaware any
                            satisfactory substitute for export controls at Hong Kong.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">McConaughy</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>